          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the process of GST reconciliation?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Three sets of data are matched each month: the sales register against GSTR-1 and e-way bill data, the purchase register against GSTR-2B, and GSTR-3B against the books and the electronic cash and credit ledgers. Differences are listed invoice by invoice, taken up with the supplier, and carried in a tracker until the credit appears or lapses."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between GSTR-2A and GSTR-2B when reconciling input tax credit?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "GSTR-2A is dynamic and keeps changing as suppliers file or amend returns, while GSTR-2B is generated once for each month and stays static. Input tax credit is claimed on the basis of GSTR-2B, so the purchase register is reconciled against 2B, and 2A is used only to trace late filing or amendments by suppliers."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which GST applies when a Delhi supplier bills a customer in Noida or Gurugram?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "IGST applies, because the place of supply lies in a different state from the supplier's location even though all three cities sit inside the National Capital Region. Delhi, Uttar Pradesh and Haryana are separate states for GST. Charging CGST and SGST instead blocks the customer's credit and needs a credit note and a fresh IGST invoice."
          }
        }
      ]
